The Bone House is still fascinated by 100 years. Take a look at the interiors from Gaudi
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the staircase resembles the backbone of a dinosaur, and the balconies are an open fish mouth.
Such is the house of Casa Batlló in Barcelona by the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
From the locals, the house earned the nickname The House of Bones thanks to its organic shapes.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stone, tiled and mosaic fragments, a scales-like facade and ubiquitous soft curves are all typical of the Art Nouveau by Antoni Gaudi.
The facade of the house plays out the dreamy lines, tender colours and textures reminiscent of nature and animals.
In a detailed observation, you can see the geometricity, rhythm and the precisely thought-out order.
At night, the entire facade of the houses is even more dramatic, illuminated to make the impression of the glitch of the colours even more amplified.
The induction and twisting of shapes appears equally in the interiors.
The wood in the waves follows the window frames, the railing, the decorative elements of the door, the peepholes and the malls.
The Batlló house, which is located in the Eixample district on the bustling Passeig shopping street Grácia No. 43, was created by the reconstruction of the 1877 house by the architect Emilio Sala Cortese.
The renovation took place for two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, had originally insisted on demolishing the old structure and building a brand new one, but soon embraced Gaudí's idea of an unusual and cheaper rebuilding.
But the Taam Batlló apartment house was not proposed by Antoni Gaudí himself.
It was co-operated with architect by architect Josep Maria Jujol.
It was on his design board that decorations for the representative apartment of the owner of the property were created and the use of the mosaic on the facade.
A number of other creators and artists also worked on the facade.
Working together on the designs of the Casa Batlló house started with Jujol's successful collaboration with Gaudi.
Yujol participated in the construction of Gaudí's house Casa Milá as well as Park Güell, which houses other of Gaudi's works.
From the locals, the house soon after completion was revived by its organic shapes, the nickname "House of Bones."
Others, because of the specific mechanism of window opening, began to call it a "slowing house."
It is also said that the Lord of St. George, the patron saint of Catalonia, is depicted at the top of the structure.
The hidden religious motifs also contain other sculptural elements of the building.
Gaudí designed for the house for his time a unique system of central heating with ventilation vents and typical chimneys.
Bizarre may seem to be their forty-five-degree slope.
In the creation of Gaudí, Gaudí absolutely disregarded the building regulations of the time and did not allow himself to be constrained by them.
At the beginning of the construction he obtained a building permit from the city, but the data provided by him were so vague that two years later, when the city council was horrified by the result and asked for a remedy.
Councillors were concerned, for example, that the structure had also affected the pillar and the public sidewalk.
There was never a correction, on the contrary: just fifteen days after the city's call to the city district, Josep Batlló applied (and successfully obtained) permission to rent the two highest floors of the building.
The owner himself moved into the lower levels.
The second-floor gallery featured a formal salon and a bedroom and a private part of the apartment on the third floor.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The entire six-story house is intersected by a staircase to climb to the roof terrace itself.
The essential elements of the redevelopment were the abolition of all the right angles and straight lines and their replacement with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of connecting space.
The social part can be completely connected by opening the parlour doors, and the larger company can communicate comfortably without at the same time preserving the privacy needed for more intimate conversations.
The house with the Gaudí reconstruction also received an unconventional roofing and two extra floors in addition to the new facade.
Also impressive is Gaudi's play with light, blue and white glazed tiles, with which the inner courtyard is lined with, and skylights.
The game of two colours adds maximum light to all floors of the house.
Simply betting on the principle that the white reflected light more than the dark, which absorbs the sun's rays.
The house Casa Batlló, which was included in the Unesco World Heritage Fund in 2005, can be visited by anyone.
On the first floor of the house, the roomiest and most ophazeshomed apartment is made available to the public.
The owners did not oppose the move until 2002, to mark the 100th anniversary of the famous creator's birth.
They remained at the tours, finding that it was a very advantageous establishment and, in addition, they extended the tours with joint and attic spaces, including the roof terrace.
Admission to the monument is by no means insignificant, at €16.50 and students, pensioners, groups and tourist card holders have a 20% discount.
The sum greatly exceeds the price of admission to other Gaudí buildings in the city.
If you want to get a taste of the real atmosphere of the house with the dragon's turrets, you have to make a quick makeover with one of the residents of the apartment building and visit it right at home.
