People will have to turn to the centre of the Services for visa applicants before the interview in the Consulatory department; the costs will be lower and the waiting time will be reduced.
From 10 January 2011, the visa-taking process at the U.S. Embassy and consulates will be changed.
with the new procedure, the majority of applicants will have to contact the Services Centre for visa applicants (accomercacked from English: ASC) before the interview at the Consulary Department.
The staff from the ASC will withdraw the biometric information of the applicant and they will be evaluated by the Consulary Department before the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages, which are the following:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, no longer to be payable for the meeting to be agreed, the second for the processing of the application and the next for the delivery of the document by the transport service.
The applicant will pay only one fee to cover all three services.
The current tariff will remain unchanged: an amount equivalent to $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visa cases with applications (including temporary workers' visas) and $390 for a visa for traders and investors.
People who want to renew their visa will not have to interview the consulator with the consulator, but will only contact the nearest ASC, where they will present their documents and take their fingerprints.
As the biometric information will be taken to ASC, applicants who will require a second meeting with an interview at the Consulatory Department will spend a shorter time here than in the past.
Likewise, those who will apply for a visa at the consulates in Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay an extra fee for the $26 service.
