But if we focus on the detail, we find things are much more complicated.
Under the Copenhagen Accord, these funds are "new and additional" to ensure that the increased burden is implemented without the detriment of Public Aid for Development.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus on what "new and an additional" means.
While the European Commission proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, have blocked the process.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits them best.
For example, the European Commission saw 2009 as a reference: international funding has been preserved and it adds 150 million to it for the three-year fast start funding title.
Other countries have selected similar references with annual payment terms or terms at the level of public aid for development.
By contrast, France considers that the financing of "all new projects" of 2010 is 'new and additional'.
In other words, there is no reference to the expenditure of previous periods or the global public aid level for the development of d'Aide publique au développement.
In particular, the total amount of support for France towards developing countries may remain constant (or even reduced), to honour its commitment to "new and additional funding "...
Another crucial element is the distribution of donations and loans.
There is no rule yet, and each chooses his or her own method of calculation.
Some, such as France, they are considering that 1€ borrowed equals €1 to the donated.
Evidently, this is hard to prove: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be documented for some of the investments that are profitable (often the projects linked to the reduction of emissions, consisting of more efficient technologies), it is foolish to present one euro that we receive as the equivalent of one euro we give... , we should not understand it as a loan price for the creditor country (i.e. the equivalent of the interest rate).
But France can only make such a justification: "compenses" its commitment of 420 million euros, of which 91.5% is made by a loan (EUR 389.8 million) and 8.5% of donations (EUR 36.11 million) - see the EU document to check it out for yourself.
It is the only country of the Union to use a loan on such a scale.
Germany has requested 46% of this place, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among others) are complying with their commitments with 100% of their donations.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union gives €1 to its promise in satisfaction, France will only give 10 centims and consider this effort to be comparable.
A beautiful juggling piece!
To summarise, in its financing of the "fast start" France operates with a double cheat: on the one hand, the development of the stock over time and, on the other hand, with a real financial burden.
Although it is spending only €36.1 million, it can convince it to spend €420 million "new and additional" in connection with his promises.
