A pesticide-related alarm that children ingest.
The 10-year-old will be devoured by 81 different chemicals one day, according to one study published this Wednesday, by the Future Generations Association (ex-Movement for Rights and Maintains of Future Generations).
The Association, which points out that its results "do not have a significant statistical value in view of the low number of samples analysed but are characteristic of the processed issue," bought between July and September foods commonly consumed in four meals and one light meal as a light snack per child of about 10 years in supermarkets in l'Oise and Paris.
These typical dishes, including official recommendations - five pieces of fresh fruit and vegetables, three dairy products and 1.5 litres of water a day - as well as confectionery, were analysed by research laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other polluting factors.
The plate's balance is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, of which 42 are carcinogenic, possible or likely, and five substances are among the clear carcinogenic substances, as well as 37 substances that could act as disruptive to internal excrement glands (PEs), according to studies by several institutions such as the International Cancer Research Center.
"While in almost all cases the legal limits for each chemical admitted individually are not exceeded, we can see well in our research that the reality in the exposure of consumers to contaminating substances, perhaps carcinogenic, and/or PE is startling," the association says.
For breakfast, butter and tea with milk contain about ten résidu from themselves with possible carcinogenic effects and three proven to be carcinogens, as is the case with about 20 residues that could disrupt the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, reported by the study as a small snack, contains traces of six chemicals, including a banned fungicidal agent in France.
The same goes for the green beans of Kenya, included in lunch, for which studies have discovered traces of strong insecticides banned in the EU.
In addition, steak from minced meat, tuna in a can and even a bun and chewing gum were riddled with pesticides and other chemicals.
In the water from the tap, the analysis revealed the presence of nitrate and chloroform.
The salmon's steak for dinner was "richest" with 34 discovered chemical residues, and even the analysis of the plastic plate used to heat meals in the microwave did not avoid analysis.
The final risk for the consumer of this "contaminating coke shell" is probably underestimated," the study suggests.
The Ecological Europe-Greens Society (EE-LV) proposed "face to the emergency" to establish a moratorium on the use of pesticides to stop the "increase of civilizational diseases."
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EFSA) examined the residue situation of 365 different pesticides identified in fruits and vegetables consumed in Europe, of which 76 in cereal.
